    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Royal Gardens Kew</hi></placeName>
                    <date>October 19/66</date>
                    <salute>My dear Darwin</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>The shrubs for your lawn are gone to day.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/> plant them singly in good light loamy soil &amp; <hi rend="underline">not too near other trees</hi>.</p>
<p>Lyell was here the other day very well, but blinder than ever I fear.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> He sent me his chapters X, XI, XIII<ref target="#foot.f3"/>   I pointed out a few inadvertencies in X &amp; XI. My great objection to XII is that he ignores vapor,—which plays so important a part in modifying climate— if you push the land to the Poles or to the Equator, you may not necessarily thereby alter the temp. of the globe.—only alter its distribution over the Globe<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>Ever yr aff | J D Hooker</p>
<p>The Govt. (Lord J. Manners) has arranged that the Treasury will propose to Parliament next session to purchase my fathers collection<ref target="#foot.f5"/></p> 
<figure type="diagram"> 
<p>Herbarium £5000</p>
<p>Choice of books £1000</p>
<p>Portraits, mss,</p>
<p>Correspondence &amp;c £1000</p>
<p>£7000</p> </figure> 
<p>This is what I asked. it relieves me of a great strain.</p>
<p>Ever yr aff | J D H</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">On 19 October 1866 Hooker sent CD the following plants: <hi rend="italic">Abies douglasii</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Pseudotsuga menziesii</hi>, Douglas fir), <hi rend="italic">A. canadensis</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Tsuga canadensis</hi>, hemlock, or <hi rend="italic">Picea glauca</hi>, white spruce), <hi rend="italic">Retinospora obtusa</hi> (unidentifiable; <hi rend="italic">Retinospora</hi> is a name formerly used for ‘many scale-leaved conifers in the juvenile needle-leaved stage’ (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5047.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Mabberley 1997</ref>)), <hi rend="italic">Wellingtonia gigantea</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Sequoiadendron giganteum</hi>, giant sequoia), <hi rend="italic">Cupressus lawsoniana</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Chamaecyparis lawsoniana</hi>, Port Orford cedar), <hi rend="italic">C. macrocarpa</hi> (Monterey cypress), and <hi rend="italic">Thujia lobbii</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Thuja plicata</hi>, western red cedar); (Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, Outwards book).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3051.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles Lyell’s</ref> eyesight had always been poor, requiring him to be read aloud to and to dictate much of what he wrote (K. M. Lyell ed. 1881, 2: 381).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Hooker refers to proof-sheets of chapters in the first volume of the tenth edition of Lyell’s <hi rend="italic">Principles of geology</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5032.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">C. Lyell 1867–8</ref>). CD had recently sent Lyell comments on the proof-sheets he had been sent (see letters to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3051.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles Lyell</ref>, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5236.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">9 October [1866]</ref> and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5239.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">12 October [1866]</ref>). Hooker wrote ‘XIII’ by mistake for ‘XII’ (see n. 4, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">In the section referred to in chapter 12 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5032.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">C. Lyell 1867–8</ref>, 1: 233–67), Lyell discussed the relationship between temperature and the relative position of land and sea. He discussed the role of the ocean in equalising and moderating temperature (<hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, pp. 236–9) but did not consider vapour in a similar context. In a <ref target="" resp="#automat">letter to Hooker, 20 October 1866</ref>, Lyell said he would send chapter 13 and hoped it would clear up difficulties arising from current climate theories that predicted huge temperature differences between the hemispheres because of the greater proportion of land in the northern hemisphere. He suggested that vapour, to which Hooker had alluded, could be a factor in equalising temperature (see K. M. Lyell ed. 1881, 2: 410–11). See also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5076.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, [after 28 April 1866]</ref> and nn. 7 and 8.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6275.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John James Robert Manners</ref> was commissioner of works (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2063.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">DNB</hi></ref>). Before his death in 1865, Hooker’s father, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2367.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Jackson Hooker</ref>, had written a memorandum stating that his herbarium would be left to his son on the understanding that it might be purchased by the government as part of the crown property attached to the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_117.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Allan 1967</ref>, pp. 216–17).</note>
        </div>        
            
